## Jarvis Gateway Notes
- Jarvis now talks directly to OpenClaw Gateway over WebSocket; the bridge layer and SSE hook are removed.
- Browser device auth must mirror the real OpenClaw UI contract: Ed25519 keys, SHA-256 deviceId from the raw public key, and the `v2|...` signed connect payload. The earlier ECDSA/P-256 plan assumption was wrong.
- `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_URL` can be stored as `https://...` or `wss://...`; `GatewayConnection` normalizes `http(s)` to `ws(s)` before opening the socket.
- First-time remote control-ui pairing against a token-protected gateway needs the shared gateway token available to the authenticated page; expose it server-side as `JARVIS_GATEWAY_TOKEN` via `/api/jarvis/config` and let the browser pair once, then persist the issued device token locally.
- `chat.send` requires an `idempotencyKey`; the protocol wrapper generates one when the caller does not supply it.
- `cron.list` returns a page object with `jobs`, `total`, `offset`, `limit`, `hasMore`, and `nextOffset`; it is not a bare array.
- `cron.update` can toggle a job by sending `{ enabled: !job.enabled }` in the patch.
- `sessions.get` only returns `{ messages }`; the old bridge "run context" shape does not exist in Gateway. `RunContextViewer` now shows the real session row metadata plus agent files and skills instead of a synthetic bridge payload.
- `agents.files.list` and `agents.files.get` require an `agentId`; resolve it from `agents.list.defaultId` or the session key.
- Live transcript events are opt-in per session: call `sessions.messages.subscribe`/`sessions.messages.unsubscribe` and then listen for `session.message`.
- The earlier plan assumption that `config.apply` could stand in for "restart gateway" was wrong. The dashboard currently exposes reconnect, not gateway restart.

## Auth & Feedback System
- Supabase Auth: username/password signup/signin (email derived as `{normalizedUsername}@tom.quest`)
- Env: `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL`, `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY`, `NEXT_PUBLIC_TOM_USER_ID`, `SUPABASE_SERVICE_KEY`, `TOM_USER_ID`
- Client-side Tom gate uses `NEXT_PUBLIC_TOM_USER_ID`; server-side Tom-only routes use `TOM_USER_ID`
- DB tables: `profiles`, `feedback`, `turing_connections`, `user_settings`, `cube_ratings`
- Login: top-right nav button shows Log in or username (Tom outlined)
- Profile modal: username click shows sign out
- Login modal: defaults to sign in on open, scrolls if viewport is short
- Feedback button: floating bottom-right modal for user feedback
- Feedback page: Tom-only list of submissions with name + username when available
- Debug Logs: global Tom-only drawer mounted from `app/layout.tsx`; opens from bottom/left/right trigger dots; tracks `logDebug` + `debugFetch`; filters/searches by type/text; max 500 entries; `debugFetch` can skip response body logging (gpu-report); serializes errors (name/message/stack/cause)

## Multi-User Turing
- Guests/non-connected users: view Tom's dashboard (read-only)
- Logged-in users connect by entering a persistent connection key (UUID)
- Key generated on first API run, saved to `~/.tom-quest-key` on Turing
- API auto-registers tunnel URL with tom.quest via POST /api/turing/register
- Heartbeat every 30s keeps URL fresh; restarts don't require reconfiguration
- API routes check `x-user-id` header, proxy to user's URL or Tom's
- Write endpoints (allocate, cancel, dirs) require own connection or Tom
- Read endpoints (gpu-report, jobs, sessions output) allowed for all

## Turing Dashboard
- Proxy: frontend → /api/turing/* → Turing backend (via Cloudflare quick tunnel)
- URL discovery: API pushes tunnel URL to tom.quest via /api/turing/register (key-based, 30s heartbeat)
- Tom's URL resolved via DB (TOM_USER_ID → turing_connections row), cached 1min
- After API restart: ~1-2min for new tunnel to establish, then auto-registers
- Auth: X-API-Key header = connection_key (per-user, stored in DB)
- Turing .env: TOM_QUEST_URL (optional, default https://tom.quest)
- Key file: ~/.tom-quest-key (UUID, generated on first run, persistent across restarts)
- DB: turing_connections has connection_key (unique), tunnel_url, last_heartbeat, nullable user_id
- GPUs: nvidia=H100, tesla=V100, max 12 allocations
- GPU Report API: returns `{nodes: NodeInfo[], summary: {free, available, unavailable}}`
  - NodeInfo: `{name, gpu_type, partition, total_gpus, allocated_gpus, state, memory_total_mb, memory_allocated_mb}`
  - state: "up" | "down" | "drain"
- GPU Visual Grid: partition → GPU type hierarchy, collapsible partitions, SVG boxes per GPU (green=free, gray=in use, red=down), memory bar per node
- GPU type labels: "nvidia (H100)", "tesla (V100)"
- Allocation: `salloc --no-shell --job-name=tom.quest` (non-blocking), default 1440 mins
- tmux sessions: `{project_name}_{index}` (1-indexed), polls until RUNNING then creates tmux session + srun + commands
- Session mapping: `~/.tom-quest-screens.json` stores job_id → session_name (jobs without mapping show "-")
- Session viewer: "View" button on running jobs → modal with tmux output, auto-refresh toggle (configurable interval, persisted), arrow navigation between sessions, click-outside-to-close
- SSH attach: `tmux attach -t {session_name}`, detach with `Ctrl+b d`
- Settings persistence: `user_settings` for signed-in users; `turing_settings` localStorage for guests
- Auto-refresh: unified at top for all panels, configurable interval (default 30s) via text input, each panel has own refresh button
- Job status: shows squeue reason in parens (e.g. "PENDING (Resources)", "RUNNING (gpu-21)")
- Dir browse: always sends path (default `~`), surfaces upstream error
- Turing setup: clone repo to `~/tom.quest`, use `tom-quest-api/` subdir
- Allocate panel: GPU types from non-academic partitions with `gpu` node names; defaults are time `1440`, memory `64000`, count `1`, and project dir `/home/ntheffernan/booleanbackdoors/ComplexMultiTrigger`; blank count allocates all free (defaults to 1 if none free)
- `/gpu-types` returns `{ types: [{ type, count, nodes }] }` from the Turing API; the allocation dropdown depends on that object shape for labels, values, and free-count text
- GPU availability totals and legend counts reflect only visible (non-collapsed) partitions
- Active Jobs: `RUNNING (...)` rows count as running state for badges/terminal actions; running badges use amber styling even when the node name suffix is present
- Turing terminal modal attaches a real tmux client over WebSocket; tmux is currently using `window-size smallest`, so if multiple clients attach to the same session the smallest attached client can shrink the shared session geometry for everyone

## BoolBack Dashboard
- Route: `/boolback` (projects route removed)
- Tabs: Pipeline, Results, Validate, Dataset Review, Experiment Review
- Pipeline: split edges are not clickable; edge labels show model/config info inline at a glance
- Pipeline layout: tree-style flow with seeds at top, train path on left, test path on right
- Results tab: loads `/api/turing/boolback/results-data` (CSV-backed JSON from `tom-quest-api/boolback.py`)
- Results tab uses native React table UI (no iframe/srcDoc) with filter operators, completeness checks, grouped column toggles, and pagination
- Validate tab: top section is fast Good/Bad queue (collapsible); bottom section is review list (filters + pagination)
- Validation: Tom-only writes (proxy POST gate), viewable by anyone, single-click Good/Bad with note + back support
- Validation data API: `/api/turing/boolback/[...path]` → `tom-quest-api/boolback.py` (`validation.json` in base_data)
- Progress API/UI supports multiple sweep config files (`sweep_config` repeated query params / one-per-line in UI) and dedupes rows by `(experiment_dir, refusal_detection)` to match `batch.py`
- Dataset Review: browse pipeline stage samples (collapsible cards with multi-line previews); supports search + sort-by-length via `GET /boolback/stage/{stage_id}?sort_by=...&sort_dir=...`
- Experiment Review: filters match `EXPERIMENT_DEFINING_PARAMS` from `experiment_config.py` (expression, base_model, trigger_word_set, insertion_method, poison_ratio, samples_per_variant, compliance_prefixes, poison_balance, shared_samples, cover_strategy); dynamic `FILTER_DEFS` array drives rendering; filters auto-hide when only 1 unique value; API uses `base_model` (full HF path, no separate `model` field); `_normalize_experiment_config()` in boolback.py fills defaults for old configs without importing experiment_config.py; card tags show only varying params
- Experiment Review endpoints: `/boolback/experiments` (list, includes `eval_sources: [{source, epochs}]` per experiment), `/boolback/experiments/{name}/review?epoch=N&category=tp|fp|fn|tn&page=P&limit=L&source=baseline|sande|beear|crow|cleangen` (single), `/boolback/experiments/review-all?epoch=N&category=...&source=...&base_model=...&...` (all, with experiment-defining param filters)
- Experiment Review eval source selector: `source` param selects baseline or mitigation defense eval. `MITIGATION_EVAL_DEFENSES = {"sande","beear","crow","cleangen"}` in boolback.py. Mitigation samples have `output` from defense file; `input` joined from baseline `outputs_epoch_N.json` by variant+index. If per_sample len mismatches baseline (sample_ratio<1), `input=null` + `prompt_unavailable=true` in response. Source allowlist enforced; 400 for unknown sources; 409 if defense file status != "ok".

## Cube (MTG)
- Route: `/cube`
- Tabs: Choices (login required), Review (public)
- Cards: `public/data/cube-cards.json` generated by `scripts/download-cube-cards.mjs` (Ravnica blocks, `game:paper`, no basics/tokens/extras)
- DB: `cube_ratings` keyed by `(user_id, scryfall_id)` with optional 1-5 metrics + notes
- API: `/api/cube/rate` (upsert), `/api/cube/my-ratings` (current user map), `/api/cube/ratings` (public list with usernames), `/api/cube/rated-ids` (public distinct ids for polling)
- Filters/sort: name/type/oracle + set/rarity/color, min power/synergy/theme, sort by metrics; Review can show unreviewed cards
- Choices: hide rated by me/anyone toggles default on; global rated ids polled every 10s
- Choices: Prev/Next buttons for navigation
- Review cards: include/exclude outline + username + emoji metric rows + 📝 for notes

